******
[2]
Date: Wed 2 Feb 2022
Source: Haber Turk [in Turkish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.haberturk.com/son-dakika-universiteliler-yemekten-zehirlendi-iddiasi-3332224


A camp was held at KTO Karatay University in the city. About 400 people, students, staff and staff, had lunch. According to the news of Zafer SamancÄ±, some of these people became ill after awhile. People with symptoms of high fever, nausea and vomiting were admitted to the hospital. Some of the students stated that they ate liver for lunch; after awhile they became nauseous and started to vomit, and when their condition worsened, they were taken to the hospital. It was learned that the number of those who applied to the hospital was around 250.

After the poisoning cases, an announcement was made on the social media accounts of KTO Karatay University. The following statements were included in the announcement: "It was seen that some people were affected due to a meal in our university cafeteria at noon today and medical attention was given quickly. It is important that our dear students and valuable educators, who feel unwell because of the food they consume in our university cafeteria, contact us quickly."

--
Communicated by:
Mahmoud Orabi
<ahstandards@gmail.com>

[ProMED thanks Mahmoud Orabi for these submissions.

Although one of the 2 reports mentioned liver as a possible source of this outbreak, which presented with fever, nausea and vomiting, it is
not stated how long after the meal (the incubation period) the symptoms began. Foodborne illnesses with primarily nausea and vomiting tend to occur without fever (i.e., staphylococcal enterotoxin induced). ProMED would appreciated more information about this outbreak.

The city of Konya is the capital of Konya Province in southwest-central Anatolia. - Mod.LL

